    "recap_headline": "University of Michigan Athletics",
    "recap_text": "\u00bb Michigan dropped the final game of the series to No. 1 UCLA.\n\u00bb\nDrew Culbertson\nwas one of two Wolverines to reach base twice, doing so with a walk and a single.\n\u00bb\nCarson Luna\nscored a run and tallied a hit in the contest.\nLOS ANGELES, Calif.\n-- The University of Michigan baseball team fell to No. 1 UCLA, 7-2, on Sunday afternoon (March 15) at Jackie Robinson Stadium.\nMichigan (9-9, 0-3 Big Ten) struggled offensively over the first five innings, recording just two baserunners during that span. Both came in the third inning when\nEvan Haeger\ndrew a one-out walk followed by a single from\nDrew Culbertson\n, but two strikeouts stranded the runners.\nUCLA (17-2, 6-0 Big Ten) opened the scoring in the first on a sacrifice fly.\nShane Brinham\nstranded the bases loaded in the second with a strikeout, but the Bruins doubled their lead with another sacrifice fly in the third. UCLA added a solo home run in the fourth and another run in the fifth.\nTyler Finkbeiner\nentered with one out in the fifth and recorded a popout and a strikeout to strand the bases loaded.\nThe Wolverines had another opportunity in the sixth after Culbertson drew a leadoff walk, but a fielder's choice, strikeout and flyout ended the threat. UCLA extended its lead in the seventh, scoring three runs on three hits to take a 7-0 advantage.\nU-M opened the eighth with a single from\nCarson Luna\n. Two walks and two hit-by-pitches brought home two runs to trim the deficit to 7-2.\nJustin Brown\npitched a 1-2-3 bottom of the eighth to give Michigan a chance, but the Wolverines managed only a leadoff walk from\nJosh Campbell\nin the ninth as UCLA secured the 7-2 win.\nMichigan returns home to begin its first homestand of the season, starting with a midweek contest against Michigan State on Wednesday (March 18) at 4 p.m. The game will be streamed on B1G+."
  },
